-- PRESS DIGEST- Financial Times - May 21
-- 
-- Tue May 20, 2014 08:44PM EDT
-- None



May 21 (Reuters) - The following are the top stories in the Financial Times. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

Headlines  PFIZER SCRAMBLES TO KEEP ASTRA BID ALIVE (http://link.reuters.com/rub59v)  GOLDMAN MOVES TO OFFLOAD METALS WAREHOUSES (http://link.reuters.com/sub59v)  CREDIT SUISSE UNDONE BY "BRAZEN" MISCONDUCT (http://link.reuters.com/tub59v)  GERMANY FINDS EVIDENCE OF FOREX RATE-FIXING (http://link.reuters.com/vub59v)  BP'S CHIEF ECONOMIST LEAVES FOR ABU DHABI INVESTMENT AUTHORITY (http://link.reuters.com/wub59v)  Overview  Pfizer <PFE.N> scrambled for support from AstraZeneca's <AZN.L> shareholders as the UK drugmaker rejected its offer of a 55 pound-per-share deal, and said there was no chance of renewed talks.   Goldman Sachs <GS.N> has started the sale procedure for Metro International Trade Services - its metal warehouses network - calling it the right time to explore a sale, and the business not strategic to its clients.   Credit Suisse's <CSGN.VX> brazen misconduct and shamefully inadequate internal inquiry led to the Swiss bank pleading guilty to criminal wrongdoing, Attorney General cited as reasons for the guilty plea.  Germany's financial watchdog charged Europe's biggest bank HSBC <HSBA.L>, U.S. bank JPMorgan <JPM.N> and France's Credit Agricole <CAGR.PA> with rigging financial benchmarks linked to the euro, exposing them to potential fines.